VSo, what I'd like to talk about is something
p4
aVthat was very dear to Kahn's heart, which is:
p5
aVhow do we discover what is really particular about a project?
p6
aVHow do you discover the uniqueness of a project as unique as a person?
p7
aVBecause it seems to me that finding this uniqueness
p8
aVhas to do with dealing with the whole force of globalization;
p9
aVthat the particular is central to finding the uniqueness of place
p10
aVand the uniqueness of a program in a building.
p11
aa(lp12
VAnd so I'll take you to Wichita, Kansas,
p13
aVwhere I was asked some years ago to do a science museum
p14
aVon a site, right downtown by the river.
p15
aVAnd I thought the secret of the site was to make the building of the river, part of the river.
p16
aVUnfortunately, though, the site was separated from the river by McLean Boulevard
p17
aVso I suggested, "Let's reroute McLean,"
p18
aVand that gave birth instantly to Friends of McLean Boulevard.
p19
aV(Laughter)
p20
aVAnd it took six months to reroute it.
p21
aa(lp22
VThe first image I showed the building committee was
p23
aVthis astronomic observatory of Jantar Mantar in Jaipur
p24
aVbecause I talked about what makes a building a building of science.
p25
aVAnd it seemed to me that this structure \u2014 complex, rich and yet
p26
aVtotally rational: it's an instrument \u2014 had something to do with science,
p27
aVand somehow a building for science should be different and unique and speak of that.
p28
aVAnd so my first sketch after I left was to say,
p29
aV"Let's cut the channel and make an island and make an island building."
p30
aVAnd I got all excited and came back, and
p31
aVthey sort of looked at me in dismay and said, "An island?
p32
aVThis used to be an island \u2014 Ackerman Island \u2014
p33
aVand we filled in the channel during the Depression to create jobs."
p34
aV(Laughter)
p35
aa(lp36
VAnd so the process began and they said,
p37
aV"You can't put it all on an island;
p38
aVsome of it has to be on the mainland because
p39
aVwe don't want to turn our back to the community."
p40
aVAnd there emerged a design: the galleries sort of forming an island
p41
aVand you could walk through them or on the roof.
p42
aVAnd there were all kinds of exciting features:
p43
aVyou could come in through the landside buildings,
p44
aVwalk through the galleries into playgrounds in the landscape.
p45
aVIf you were cheap you could walk on top of a bridge to the roof,
p46
aVpeek in the exhibits and then get totally seduced,
p47
aVcome back and pay the five dollars admission.
p48
aV(Laughter)
p49
aVAnd the client was happy \u2014 well, sort of happy
p50
aVbecause we were four million dollars over the budget, but essentially happy.
p51
aa(lp52
VBut I was still troubled, and I was troubled because I felt this was capricious.
p53
aVIt was complex, but there was something capricious about its complexity.
p54
aVIt was, what I would say, compositional complexity,
p55
aVand I felt that if I had to fulfill what I talked about \u2014
p56
aVa building for science \u2014 there had to be some kind of a generating idea,
p57
aVsome kind of a generating geometry.
p58
aVAnd this gave birth to the idea of having toroidal generating geometry,
p59
aVone with its center deep in the earth for the landside building
p60
aVand a toroid with its center in the sky for the island building.
p61
aVA toroid, for those who don't know,
p62
aVis the surface of a doughnut or, for some of us, a bagel.
p63
aVAnd out of this idea started spinning off many,
p64
aVmany kinds of variations of different plans and possibilities,
p65
aVand then the plan itself evolved in relationship to the exhibits,
p66
aVand you see the intersection of the plan with the toroidal geometry.
p67
aa(lp68
VAnd finally the building \u2014 this is the model.
p69
aVAnd when there were complaints about budget, I said,
p70
aV"Well, it's worth doing the island because you get twice for your money: reflections."
p71
aVAnd here's the building as it opened,
p72
aVwith a channel overlooking downtown, and as seen from downtown.
p73
aVAnd the bike route's going right through the building,
p74
aVso those traveling the river would see the exhibits and be drawn to the building.
p75
aVThe toroidal geometry made for a very efficient building:
p76
aVevery beam in this building is the same radius, all laminated wood.
p77
aVEvery wall, every concrete wall is resisting the stresses and supporting the building.
p78
aVEvery piece of the building works.
p79
aVThese are the galleries with the light coming in through the skylights,
p80
aVand at night, and on opening day.
