aa(lp82
VGoing back to 1976.
p83
aV(Applause)
p84
aVIn 1976, I was asked to design a children's memorial museum
p85
aVin a Holocaust museum in Yad Vashem in Jerusalem,
p86
aVwhich you see here the campus.
p87
aVI was asked to do a building,
p88
aVand I was given all the artifacts of clothing and drawings.
p89
aVAnd I felt very troubled.
p90
aVI worked on it for months and I couldn't deal with it
p91
aVbecause I felt people were coming out of the historic museum,
p92
aVthey are totally saturated with information
p93
aVand to see yet another museum with information,
p94
aVit would make them just unable to digest.
p95
aVAnd so I made a counter-proposal:
p96
aa(lp97
VI said, "No building." There was a cave on the site; we tunnel into the hill,
p98
aVdescend through the rock into an underground chamber.
p99
aVThere's an anteroom with photographs of children who perished
p100
aVand then you come into a large space.
p101
aVThere is a single candle flickering in the center;
p102
aVby an arrangement of reflective glasses, it reflects into infinity in all directions.
p103
aVYou walk through the space, a voice reads the names,
p104
aVages and place of birth of the children.
p105
aVThis voice does not repeat for six months.
p106
aVAnd then you descend to light and to the north and to life.
p107
aa(lp108
VWell, they said, "People won't understand,
p109
aVthey'll think it's a discotheque. You can't do that."
p110
aVAnd they shelved the project. And it sat there for 10 years,
p111
aVand then one day Abe Spiegel from Los Angeles,
p112
aVwho had lost his three-year-old son at Auschwitz,
p113
aVcame, saw the model, wrote the check and it got built 10 years later.
