aa(lp115
VSo, many years after that in 1998,
p116
aVI was on one of my monthly trips to Jerusalem
p117
aVand I got a call from the foreign ministry saying,
p118
aV"We've got the Chief Minister of the Punjab here.
p119
aVHe is on a state visit. We took him on a visit to Yad Vashem,
p120
aVwe took him to the children's memorial; he was extremely moved.
p121
aVHe's demanding to meet the architect. Could you come down and meet him in Tel Aviv?"
p122
aVAnd I went down and Chief Minister Badal said to me,
p123
aV"We Sikhs have suffered a great deal, as you have Jews.
p124
aVI was very moved by what I saw today.
p125
aVWe are going to build our national museum to tell the story of our people;
p126
aVwe're about to embark on that.
p127
aVI'd like you to come and design it."
p128
aa(lp129
VAnd so, you know, it's one of those things that you don't take too seriously.
p130
aVBut two weeks later, I was in this little town, Anandpur Sahib,
p131
aVoutside Chandigarh, the capital of the Punjab,
p132
aVand the temple and also next to it the fortress
p133
aVthat the last guru of the Sikhs, Guru Gobind, died in
p134
aVas he wrote the Khalsa, which is their holy scripture.
p135
aVAnd I got to work and they took me somewhere down there,
p136
aVnine kilometers away from the town and the temple,
p137
aVand said, "That's where we have chosen the location."
p138
aa(lp139
VAnd I said, "This just doesn't make any sense.
p140
aVThe pilgrims come here by the hundreds of thousands \u2014
p141
aVthey're not going to get in trucks and buses and go down there.
p142
aVLet's get back to the town and walk to the site."
p143
aVAnd I recommended they do it right there, on that hill
p144
aVand this hill, and bridge all the way into the town.
p145
aVAnd, as things are a little easier in India, the site was purchased within a week
p146
aVand we were working.
p147
aV(Laughter)
p148
aa(lp149
VAnd my proposal was to split the museum into two \u2014
p150
aVthe permanent exhibits at one end, the auditorium, library,
p151
aVand changing exhibitions on the other \u2014
p152
aVto flood the valley into a series of water gardens
p153
aVand to link it all to the fort and to the downtown.
p154
aVAnd the structures rise from the sand cliffs \u2014
p155
aVthey're built in concrete and sandstones; the roofs are stainless steel \u2014
p156
aVthey are facing south and reflecting light towards the temple itself,
p157
aVpedestrians crisscross from one side to the other.
p158
aVAnd as you come from the north, it is all masonry growing out of the sand cliffs
p159
aVas you come from the Himalayas and evoking the tradition of the fortress.
