aa(lp253
VI'd like to conclude by saying something ...
p254
aV(Applause)
p255
aVI'd like to conclude by relating all of what I've said to the term "beauty."
p256
aVAnd I know it is not a fashionable term these days,
p257
aVand certainly not fashionable in the discourse of architectural schools,
p258
aVbut it seems to me that all this, in one way or the other, is a search for beauty.
p259
aVBeauty in the most profound sense of fit.
p260
aVI have a quote that I like by a morphologist, 1917,
p261
aVTheodore Cook, who said, "Beauty connotes humanity.
p262
aVWe call a natural object beautiful because we see
p263
aVthat its form expresses fitness, the perfect fulfillment of function."
p264
aVWell, I would have said the perfect fulfillment of purpose.
p265
aVNevertheless, beauty as the kind of fit; something that tells us
p266
aVthat all the forces that have to do with our natural environment
p267
aVhave been fulfilled \u2014 and our human environment \u2014 for that.
p268
aa(lp269
VTwenty years ago, in a conference Richard and I were at together,
p270
aVI wrote a poem, which seems to me to still hold for me today.
p271
aV"He who seeks truth shall find beauty. He who seeks beauty shall find vanity.
p272
aVHe who seeks order shall find gratification.
p273
aVHe who seeks gratification shall be disappointed.
p274
aVHe who considers himself the servant of his fellow beings
p275
aVshall find the joy of self-expression. He who seeks self-expression
p276
aVshall fall into the pit of arrogance.
p277
aVArrogance is incompatible with nature.
p278
aVThrough nature, the nature of the universe and the nature of man,
p279
aVwe shall seek truth. If we seek truth, we shall find beauty."
